1. Introduction
On the left you’ll see all the sections in this video. I’ve put timestamped links to each section in the description below. While you’re down there please hit the thumbs up button to help YouTube to suggest this video to others like you. 70% of the people who watch my videos are not subscribed. Please consider subscribing and hit the notification bell if you want to be notified about upcoming reviews.

It's no secret that I'm a huge fan of Cube Controls and their products. Ever since I saw the CSX2 a few years ago, I just got this feeling when I heard their name being mentioned. I thought I'd never own any of their equipment and who knows, if it wasn't for this channel, I'm not sure I would ever have gotten to this stage.

So when I first saw these pedals in 2021, I was blown away. I thought they were the most beautiful pedals I'd ever seen. The blue finish with the strong but intricate structure, the smooth pedal faces and pops of bright iconic cube controls colour. I really was taken aback by them. By the time I finally got to try them for the first time, I had a lot more experience with high end brakes, which really helped me to stay grounded while reviewing these pedals.

All of the products in this review were sent to me free of charge for the purposes of this review and nobody other than me has had any say in the content of this video. The links to this product and its competitors in the description are affiliate links and if used will earn this channel some money at no extra cost to you.

2. First Impressions
They look great on camera, but in person, they're even nicer. The quality of the powder coating, the shapes and subtleties are really nice. The release of these pedals took so long though that I actually overlooked one major thing. They never released a clutch pedal. So you'll have to forgive me, as I used my review hardware for all of my league races, and I can't do that without a clutch pedal. So I've had to use the Meca Evo clutch pedal and baseplate for this review.



